Review this Go code for a real bug:
```go
func Sum(nums []int) int {
	var total int
	for i := 1; i <= len(nums); i++ {
		total += nums[i]
	}
	return total
}
```

response:
**Bug: off-by-one that indexes out of bounds.** The loop runs `i` from `1` to `len(nums)` inclusive. Two problems: it skips `nums[0]`, and on the last iteration `i == len(nums)` indexes one past the end, so `nums[i]` panics with `index out of range`.

Use a `range` loop, which visits every element by value and can never go out of bounds:

```go
func Sum(nums []int) int {
	total := 0
	for _, n := range nums {
		total += n
	}
	return total
}
```

