Review this Go code and identify the bug, explain why it happens, and show the corrected version:

```go
func startWorkers(tasks []string) {
	var wg sync.WaitGroup
	for _, t := range tasks {
		wg.Add(1)
		go func() {
			defer wg.Done()
			fmt.Println(t)
		}()
	}
	wg.Wait()
}
```

response:
**Bug: loop-variable capture.** Each goroutine closes over the single loop variable `t`, not a per-iteration copy. By the time the goroutines run, the loop has usually finished, so they all observe the *last* value of `t` (and you'll see duplicated/last-only output rather than every task).

Note: in Go 1.22+ the loop variable is per-iteration, so this specific snippet is safe there — but relying on that is fragile and breaks on older toolchains and in linters. Make the intent explicit.

