instruction:
Review this Go code; under load it leaks timers and memory. Explain why and fix:

```go
func poll(ch <-chan int) {
	for {
		select {
		case v := <-ch:
			process(v)
		case <-time.After(time.Second):
			fmt.Println("idle")
		}
	}
}
```

response:
**Bug: `time.After` allocates a new timer on every loop iteration, and it isn't garbage-collected until it fires.** Each time the `ch` case is taken, the `time.After(time.Second)` timer created for that iteration is abandoned — but the runtime keeps it alive for its full 1-second duration. In a hot loop receiving many values per second, you accumulate thousands of pending timers, wasting memory and scheduler work until each expires. The `time.After` doc explicitly warns about this for loops.

**Fix — create one timer and `Reset` it each iteration:**

```go
func poll(ch <-chan int) {
	timer := time.NewTimer(time.Second)
	defer timer.Stop()
	for {
		timer.Reset(time.Second) // reuse the same timer
		select {
		case v := <-ch:
			process(v)
		case <-timer.C:
			fmt.Println("idle")
		}
	}
}
```

A single `time.NewTimer` reused via `Reset` avoids per-iteration allocation. (If "idle" means a true periodic tick regardless of activity, a `time.NewTicker` is even simpler.) The rule: `time.After` is fine for a one-shot timeout, but never call it inside a tight or long-running loop — reuse a `Timer`/`Ticker` instead.

